{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "For years, each shot fired by a New York City police officer has been meticulously studied, but not the more routine episodes of force, like baton blows and takedowns.", "abstract": "New York Police Dept is for first time instituting sweeping new guidelines governing officers' use of force and means of tracking incidents; rules, set to go into effect in early 2016, require officers to document every instance when force is used, no matter how minor; officers will also now face formal discipline not only if they fail to report instances of excessive force, but also if they fail to summon medical help for anyone requesting it. ", "section_name": "N.Y. / Region", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Al", "role": "reported", "lastname": "BAKER", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"lastname": "GOODMAN", "rank": 2, "firstname": "J.", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "David"}], "original": "By AL BAKER and J. DAVID GOODMAN", "contributor": "Susan C. Beachy contributed research."}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/01/nyregion/new-york-police-will-document-virtually-all-instances-of-force.html", "lead_paragraph": "For years, each shot fired by a New York City police officer has been meticulously studied, but not the more routine episodes of force, like baton blows and takedowns.", "headline": {"main": "New York Police Will Document Virtually All Instances of Force", "print_headline": "New York Police to Strictly Track the Use of Force"}, "_id": "560cb01838f0d8716779a9ab", "word_count": "1495", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/10/01/nyregion/FORCEjp1-y/FORCEjp1-y-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/10/01/nyregion/FORCEjp1-y/FORCEjp1-y-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2015/10/01/nyregion/FORCEjp1-y/FORCEjp1-y-articleLarge.jpg", "